dataCopy = data.copy(deep=True)
column_distributions = {}

for col in dataCopy.columns:
    col_data = dataCopy[col]

    # Determine column data type and prepare summary statistics accordingly
    if pd.api.types.is_numeric_dtype(col_data):
        # For numeric columns, calculate min, max, mean, and top values
        col_summary = {
            "Data Type": col_data.dtype,
            "Null Count": col_data.isnull().sum(),
            "Unique Values": col_data.nunique(),
            "Max Value": col_data.max(),
            "Min Value": col_data.min(),
            "Mean Value": col_data.mean(),
            "Most Common Values": col_data.value_counts().head(5).to_dict()  
        }

        plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
        col_data.dropna().value_counts().sort_index().plot(
            kind='bar', color='skyblue', edgecolor='black')
        plt.title(f'Distribution of {col}')
        plt.xlabel(col)
        plt.ylabel('Frequency')
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.show()

    else:
        # For non-numeric columns, ensure consistent type handling
        col_data_numeric = pd.to_numeric(col_data, errors='coerce')
        if col_data_numeric.notnull().any():
            # Handle mixed or numeric-like non-numeric columns
            col_data = col_data_numeric

        # Calculate top values and unique count
        col_summary = {
            "Data Type": col_data.dtype,
            "Null Count": col_data.isnull().sum(),
            "Unique Values": col_data.nunique(),
            "Most Common Values": col_data.value_counts().head(5).to_dict()  # Top 5 common values
        }

        col_data_cleaned = col_data.dropna()
        if pd.api.types.is_numeric_dtype(col_data_cleaned):
            unique_vals = sorted(col_data_cleaned.unique())
            plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
            plt.hist(col_data_cleaned, bins=len(unique_vals), color='skyblue', edgecolor='black', align='left')
            plt.title(f'Distribution of {col}')
            plt.xlabel(col)
            plt.ylabel('Frequency')
            plt.show()
        else:
            # Plot bar chart for categorical data
            plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
            col_data_cleaned.value_counts().plot(kind='bar', color='coral', edgecolor='black')
            plt.title(f'Distribution of {col}')
            plt.xlabel('Unique Values')
            plt.ylabel('Count')
            plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
            plt.show()

    # Store the summary for the column
    column_distributions[col] = col_summary

# Convert the dictionary to a DataFrame for a structured view
distributions_df = pd.DataFrame(column_distributions).T

# Display the results
print(distributions_df)

NOTES from the visualizations above - Total data points 456. Years for data - 7

  1. April and May seem to be peak months where abuse takes place. (Further year-month analysis done below)
  2. Our dataset has most datapoints for the year 2023, which can be due to discrepancy in data collection (INVESTIGATE)
  3. Children of age 12, 5 and 13 seem to be the most targetted age group of children
  4. Female children are MORE LIKELY TO BE ABUSED than Male children.
  5. Sexual and Physical Abuse are the major categories of abuse taking place according to our dataset.
  6. White children are more likely to be abused
  7. The offenders are also mostly white

Personal Notes - The data is very skewed due to multiple reasons. We would need to investigate why these peaks exist and if there is a discrepancy in data collection. Compare with the existing higher governmenet level datasets to verify if these patterns exist there as well to find conclusive evidence for patterns observed.

# Initialize a dictionary to store counts for each unique type of abuse
abuse_counts = {}

abuse_mapping = {
    'Physical': 'Physical Abuse',
    'Physical Abuse': 'Physical Abuse',
    'Physial Abuse': 'Physical Abuse',
    'Sexual': 'Sexual Abuse',  # Standardize any other variations as needed
    # Add more mappings if other types have variations
}

# Initialize a dictionary to store counts for each unique type of abuse
abuse_counts = {}

# Split, map, and count occurrences of each type of abuse
for entry in data['Type of Abuse '].dropna():
    types = entry.split('/')  # Split by '/' for multiple types in one cell
    for abuse_type in types:
        abuse_type = abuse_type.strip()  # Remove extra spaces if any
        # Map to standard type if in abuse_mapping, otherwise keep as is
        standardized_type = abuse_mapping.get(abuse_type, abuse_type)
        if standardized_type in abuse_counts:
            abuse_counts[standardized_type] += 1
        else:
            abuse_counts[standardized_type] = 1

# Convert the counts dictionary to a DataFrame for easier plotting
abuse_counts_df = pd.DataFrame(list(abuse_counts.items()), columns=['Type of Abuse', 'Count'])
abuse_counts_df = abuse_counts_df.sort_values(by='Count', ascending=False)

# Plot the results
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.bar(abuse_counts_df['Type of Abuse'], abuse_counts_df['Count'], color='skyblue', edgecolor='black')
plt.title('Distribution of Types of Abuse')
plt.xlabel('Type of Abuse')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.tight_layout()  # Adjust layout to fit labels better
plt.show()

bars = plt.bar(abuse_counts_df['Type of Abuse'], abuse_counts_df['Count'], color='skyblue', edgecolor='black')

for bar in bars:
    yval = bar.get_height()
    plt.text(
        bar.get_x() + bar.get_width()/2, yval + 3,  # Adjust yval for more spacing above bar
        int(yval),
        ha='center',
        va='bottom',
        fontsize=12,
        fontweight='bold'
    )

plt.tight_layout(pad=1.5, w_pad=0.9, h_pad=4.0, rect=[0, 0, 2, 2])
plt.show()

import pandas as pd

# Function to convert age with months to years, handles possible missing data or errors
def convert_age_to_years(age):
    if isinstance(age, str) and "months" in age.lower():
        # Extract the number of months from the string and convert to years
        months = int(age.split()[0])  # Extract the number part (before the 'Months' string)
        return months / 12  # Convert months to years
    else:
        # If the value is numeric or already in years, return it as is
        return float(age)

# Apply the conversion to the "Child Age" column
data['Child Age'] = data['Child Age'].apply(convert_age_to_years)

# Verifying if the conversion worked
print(data['Child Age'][33])

# Function to perform the analysis and plotting for any year
def plot_trends_by_year(data, year=None):
    # Filter by year if specified, else use all data
    if year:
        data = data[data['Year Seen'] == year]

    # Group by 'Month Seen', 'Type of Abuse', 'Child Gender', 'Child Race' to get the count of cases
    monthly_abuse_summary = data.groupby(['Month Seen', 'Type of Abuse ', 'Child Gender', 'Child Race'])['Child Age'].count().reset_index(name='Number of Cases')

    # Get all unique 'Type of Abuse' to create distinct colors
    abuse_types = monthly_abuse_summary['Type of Abuse '].unique()
    
    # Generate a color palette based on the number of abuse types
    palette = sns.color_palette("Set2", n_colors=len(abuse_types))
    
    # Plot 1: Stacked Bar Plot for Type of Abuse and Gender (for all years or a specific year)
    plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))
    monthly_abuse_summary_pivot = monthly_abuse_summary.pivot_table(
        index=['Month Seen', 'Child Gender'], columns='Type of Abuse ', values='Number of Cases', aggfunc='sum', fill_value=0)

    monthly_abuse_summary_pivot.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, color=palette, figsize=(12, 8))
    plt.title(f'Number of Cases by Type of Abuse and Gender ({year if year else "All Years"})')
    plt.xlabel('Month and Gender')
    plt.ylabel('Number of Cases')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend(title='Type of Abuse', loc='upper left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    # Plot 2: Line Plot for Trends in Mean Age Across Months
    monthly_age_summary = data.groupby(['Month Seen'])['Child Age'].mean().reset_index(name='Mean Age')
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
    sns.lineplot(data=monthly_age_summary, x='Month Seen', y='Mean Age', marker='o', color='purple')
    plt.title(f'Mean Age of Children by Month ({year if year else "All Years"})')
    plt.xlabel('Month')
    plt.ylabel('Mean Age')
    plt.xticks(range(1, 13), ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec'])
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    # Plot 3: Monthly Trends for Sexual Abuse by Gender
    sexual_abuse_data = data[data['Type of Abuse '] == 'Sexual Abuse']
    sexual_abuse_monthly = sexual_abuse_data.groupby(['Month Seen', 'Child Gender'])['Child Age'].count().reset_index(name='Number of Cases')
    plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))
    sns.lineplot(data=sexual_abuse_monthly, x='Month Seen', y='Number of Cases', hue='Child Gender', marker='o', palette='Set1')
    plt.title(f'Monthly Trends of Sexual Abuse by Gender ({year if year else "All Years"})')
    plt.xlabel('Month')
    plt.ylabel('Number of Cases')
    plt.xticks(range(1, 13), ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec'])
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Call the function for all years
plot_trends_by_year(data)
